      <div class="annotationBody">
        <div class="annotationQuote">The use of student learning objectives/outcomes (SLOs) isn’t helping differentiate teacher performance.</div>
        <div><p>This is because SLO's are a failure. Trying to have all teachers base their goals on student growth is a fallacy. I know the "alternative" is to judge teachers solely on HST testing but then you have art teachers judged on reading scores...that's silly...so in an effort to create "objectivity" teachers have to right SLO's. These contribute to overtesting, fall victim to Campbell's Law, and make no sense.</p>

<p>Why can't a goal for an art teahcer be: "Create a community based art show that connects students to local artists..."</p>

<p>Because it can't be quantified. </p>

<p>SLOs need reform.</p></div>
