      <div class="annotationBody">
        
        <div><p>The point of the exercise was not to gain a deep read of the article - in that respect, it is an "unjournal club" not a journal club.  My goal (although obviously everyone can have their own goals but here's the original goal) was to bring a sense of discomfort to the academic who is already too comfortable with the old journal club routine - to increase the facility w/ which they deal with unfamiliarity; to help them learn how to cope with the disorientation of following multiple streams at the same time.  It's a form of twitter literacy practice.  Moreover, I wanted people to think creatively - to spring *from * the article versus dig deep into the article to make their connections.  A glancing familiarity with the article, rather than a careful pre-read, makes that more feasible (that's a hypothesis, not a statement of fact).</p>

<p>So, as I've said to Yin several times, the unjournal club has nontraditional learning objectives. If we go by the traditional standards, the points made above (and her's) are extremely valid.  If we go by mine...well, that's a conversation I want to have and the point of continued experimentation.</p>

<p>And thanks for being cool :)</p></div>
